> ‘man’). The word is attested in this sense from the 15th century, but is not used specifically for the leader of a gang of workers before the late 16th century.","English: variant of <b>Fordman</b> with loss of <i>-d-</i>, from Middle English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ (Old English <i>ford</i>) + <i>man</i>, denoting either a dweller by or a keeper of a ford. Compare   Forder  .","Americanized form of German <b>Fohrmann</b> (see   Fohrman  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705201,"age":114,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Foreman was born in 1435, in Kent, England. He married Jane. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1435–":"1435–Surnud","1437–Female":"1437–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1461–1492":"1461–1492","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1461":"1461","1492":"1492","1549":"1549","about 1461":"umbes 1461","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1435–":"1435–Kuollut","1437–Female":"1437–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1461–1492":"1461–1492","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1461":"1461","1492":"1492","1549":"1549","about 1461":"noin 1461","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"1435–":"1435–Décédé","1437–Female":"1437–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1461–1492":"1461–1492","1435–Male":"1435–Décédé","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1461":"1461","1492":"1492","1549":"1549","about 1461":"environ 1461","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Foreman est né en 1435, à Kent, Angleterre. Il a épousé Jane. Il est décédé dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1435–":"1435–Verstorben","1437–Female":"1437–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1461–1492":"1461–1492","1435–Male":"1435–Verstorben","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1461":"1461","1492":"1492","1549":"1549","about 1461":"um 1461","Kent, England":"Kent, England","lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Foreman wurde 1435 in Kent, England g